column6: https://www.telesurtv.net/english/news/Whos-Who-in-Honduras-General-Elections-20171120-0002.html "The top three candidates, according to most surveys, are Hernandez, Nasralla and Medrano. In October, Encuestadora Paradigma ranked them at 42.5 percent, 19.8 percent and nine percent respectively. Meanwhile, Moreno Research placed the same candidates at 46 percent, 23 percent and 12 percent." and https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/23/opinion/honduras-juan-orlando-hernandez-election.html?_r=0 "It’s possible that Mr. Nasralla would win a free and fair election, as there is plenty of opposition to Mr. Hernández’s re-election — nearly two-thirds of Hondurans oppose re-election. But Mr. Hernández and his allies control the much-protested ballot-counting process, the election oversight commission, the army — which under Honduran law moves the ballots — and all appeals processes. Given his total control over the election process, we can’t expect him and his corrupt manipulators to allow a free and fair election to decide their fate."
No major changes in thinking since previous forecasts ... just less time (as the weeks pass by) that some major circuit-breaking event will disrupt JOH's likely re-election with 48-50% of the vote.

I concocted a model that is least favorable to JOH, within the confines of being in accord with the two poll results considered (Sep Gallup, Oct Paradigma). The key to this model is splitting the undecideds as follows: 1/2 goes for Nasrallah, 1/4 for JOH and 1/4 for the rest. I also modelled stochastically the turnouts, separately for each bloc (assuming them to be highest for the challenger, lowest for the incumbent). In the end this yielded an expected margin for JOH of only 4.7%. The answer still have not moved much from my previous, more lopsided model! But, interestingly, a tiny chance emerges for JOH to lose in this scenario. So I'm putting that in, just to exhibit my contrarian streak...

Read a commentary article - apparently there is a polling blackout in the month before the election ... which explains the lack of polling data. I guess that means we can all try to over-interpret the single Cid/Gallup poll!

Assuming support levels unchanged from the Sep Cid/Gallup results: 37%,22%,17%,2% http://criterio.hn/2017/09/21/partido-liberal-libre-descalifican-encuesta-cid-gallup/ Model now disregards the undecided/nonresponse portion altogether, and proportions the 4-way numbers to 100% total; the large change in the result, versus my prior outcome when the undecideds was not taken out from the total, shows the crucial impact of what happens with that portion.

So a couple of hours reading around various sources ...

Hard to come up with a number given the new moving parts in this election. For example, I read that 2/3rds of Hondurans don't support the idea of a President having 2 terms but according to polls, people support Hernandez anyway. Hernandez won in 2013 with 36.89% of the vote beating liberal parties split between 3 candidates. This election has an alliance headed by Nasralla who got 13.43% in the 2013 race running with Castro (the wife of the deposed leader in 2009) who got 28.78% in the 2013 race.

This guy was once a student of mine, but we haven't been in touch for several years. In situations like this, I always have a hard time stifling my personal feelings and sticking with the probabilities. Not sure yet how well I'm doing it this time, especially since he is getting mixed reviews at home.
